36,0.13530068,-0.03285953,0.01330815,0.00560807,-0.02536329,-0.02092519,0.04107539,0.03347325,0.02643624,0.02948077,0.02924387,-0.04174833,0.02959699,-0.04577351,0.00144860,-0.03028299,0.01738775,-0.03250373,0.02335795,0.03052807,-0.07035549,-0.00899063,0.00637130,0.02583545,-0.03562777,-0.10355030,-0.05887298,0.01073144,0.02863139,0.02571769,-0.02358957,-0.01913618,0.01645746,0.04950046,-0.02885169,0.03379164,-0.03363638,-0.00412135,0.05959402,-0.05014563,0.06593727,0.04286071,-0.00464692]',E'Passing Functions to Spark\n\n{% highlight python %}\nclass MyClass(object):\n    def func(self, s):\n        return s\n    def doStuff(self, rdd):\n        return rdd.map(self.func)\n{% endhighlight %}\n\nHere, if we create a `new MyClass` and call `doStuff` on it, the `map` inside there references the\n`func` method *of that `MyClass` instance*, so the whole object needs to be sent to the cluster.\n\nIn a similar way, accessing fields of the outer object will reference the whole object:','{"source": "spark", "version": "3.5", "language": "python", "title": "Overview", "section_title": "rdd-programming-guide", "url": "https://github.com/apache/spark/blob/master/docs/rdd-programming-guide.md", "topics": "spark,bigdata,sql,rdd,programming,guide", "categories": "bigdata,analytics,ml,streaming"}');
