52,0.02412603,-0.03034375,0.01296994,0.04249186,0.03802087,-0.01730769,0.05186746,-0.02193618,-0.00416984,0.00583272,0.00430463,-0.00516591,0.04661477,0.02731374,-0.00431502,0.05733125,0.02032337,0.03090068,-0.02347060,-0.05126917,0.02897144,0.03830113,-0.04479863,-0.00413698,-0.05571253,-0.02473318,-0.01574599,0.04039938,0.03418428,-0.03772229,0.04704164,0.06139112,0.02874224,0.00926576,-0.02155968,0.03892534,-0.01483702,0.09979800,0.02002070,0.03043098,-0.01318263,-0.00750420]',E'Which Storage Level to Choose?\n\nSpark''s storage levels are meant to provide different trade-offs between memory usage and CPU\nefficiency. We recommend going through the following process to select one:\n\n* If your RDDs fit comfortably with the default storage level (`MEMORY_ONLY`), leave them that way.\n  This is the most CPU-efficient option, allowing operations on the RDDs to run as fast as possible.','{"source": "spark", "version": "3.5", "language": "python", "title": "Overview", "section_title": "rdd-programming-guide", "url": "https://github.com/apache/spark/blob/master/docs/rdd-programming-guide.md", "topics": "spark,bigdata,sql,rdd,programming,guide", "categories": "bigdata,analytics,ml,streaming"}');
